Grammar on the fly
Incant is homoiconic: a grammar rule is a field, and a field is a first-class object. grammarOnTheFly is a short file that demonstrates what that means in practice — a live grammar mutation, a self-capture, and a file write, all from running incant code.
Its crux is three lines:
DelimText isRule '('- dtext^}=delimiter;
DatA += DelimText;
guard(DatA);
DelimText is a new rule that captures everything between ( and a closing delimiter string. += appends it as a live alternative to DatA, one of incant's 32 bootstrap rules. guard(DatA) clears the cached guard set so the parser re-derives it after seeing DelimText for the first time.
On the very next definition, incant parses a 3654-byte comment block through the alternative that did not exist when the session began. No recompile, no restart, no grammar file rewrite. The parser's own rule table is a live data structure, reachable and writable from incant code. The locomotive changes while the train stays on schedule.
The demonstration goes one step further. grammarOnTheFly uses printTO to feed the captured comment into a buffer field, then writes it to disk using a modifiable operator writable at runtime:
modedOP operateMethod=setFileOp;            // rebinds modedOP's function pointer to setFileOp,
                                            // a wrapper method that works as an incant operator
doc modedOP "incant/grammarOnTheFly.out";   // fires setFileOp: doc is target, path is argument
closeFile(doc);
Note: grammarOnTheFly was written not because writing a file is hard, and neither is adding a comment to the top of one. It was written to show that incant can capture its own documentation through a grammar rule that didn't exist at startup, then write the proof to disk.
stop() exits and leaves the original bootstrap grammar in place so the graft does not persist. The proof is not a toy string — it is a lengthy comment block captured through the rule that wasn't there when incant started.

⏺ Here's how modedOP works and how to use it. I confirmed all of this against the source — it's real and wired, with a working
  example in incant/grammarOnTheFly.

  What modedOP is

  modedOP is an operator whose method (gOp) is settable — a "writable operator." It's an ordinary infix operator registered in
  the Operators registry, but the design intent is that the function it dispatches to can be re-pointed. Right now its method
  is bound once at startup; true runtime rebinding from incant is the deferred next step (the boundTo task still on the
  TODO).

  The three pieces that wire it up

  1. The shim — Instruct.rtn:569. A binary-operator method with the standard (argument, &target) shape (same as opAssign):

  extern GroupItem setFileOp(GroupItem argument, GroupItem &target)
  {
      if target.isBUFFER  target.buffer.setFile(argument.text);
      return target;
  }
  Left operand = target (a buffer), right operand = argument (the path text).

  2. The registration — incant/setup:82, in the Operators registry:

  modedOP operateMethod=setFileOp;
  operateMethod= is what binds the gOp slot (via setOperat(dlsym("setFileOp"))). This is the operator analog of
  interpretMethod=/ruleMethod=; it's tag-gated to the gOp/isOperator path.

  3. The use site — write it as an infix operator, target modedOP argument:

  doc modedOP "/Users/.../incant/grammarOnTheFly.out";
  doc is the target (must be a buffer), the string is the argument. This fires setFileOp, pointing doc's buffer at that file.

  The minimal end-to-end example

  This is exactly the pattern in incant/grammarOnTheFly (your working test file):

  doc buffer;                                      # 1. doc is a buffer field
  ...                                              # (fill doc with content)
  doc modedOP "/path/to/output.out";               # 2. point doc's buffer at a file
  closeFile(doc);                                  # 3. flush/close → content written

  So the operator's job here is "attach this buffer to this file." Because the method is bound through operateMethod=, the
  same modedOP symbol could later be re-pointed at a different method — that's the "moded" part, and the not-yet-built half.

  The current limitation (matches the TODO)

  The gOp is pre-bound in setup. Rebinding from incant at runtime (modedOP operateMethod=...; as a live statement, or aliasing
  via modedOP.boundTo) is not done yet — that's the open modedOP.boundTo design+impl pair in your Pre-Session Tasks. = will
  not rebind it (=/setContent ignores gOp — the poochifier), which is exactly why rebinding has to route through
  operateMethod/setOperat.

